metadata.value: TIMOTHY FORD'S HOUSE 54 Meeting Street c. 1800 Very handsome house in Adam style. Built by Timothy Ford, a veteran of the Revolution from New Jersey who became a Charleston- ian. Lafayette entertained here. Shown by candlelight. JOSEPH WINTHROP'S HOUSE 129 Tradd Street c. 1797 Handsome rooms, panelled with lew-country Cypress, show how a merchant of Charleston once lived'Othniel Beale was also colonel of provincial troops. House one of first reclaimed from slums in the area, in 1931. YOUNG-JOHNSON HOUSE 35 Church Street c. 1770 COLONEL OTHNIEL BEALE'S HOUSE 101 East Bay Street c. 1740 Long the home of Dr. Joseph Johnson, physician, historian, intendant of Charleston, and president of the city's branch of the second Bank of the United States. The furnishings ably demonstrate the harmonious blending of many periods and many styles. WILLIAM GIBBES' HOUSE 64 South Battery c. 1772 1951 CHARLESTON'S HISTORIC HOUSES March 19 to April 14, 1951 Almost a century of history and architecture will be on parade, when eighteen of the country's finest early American homes, dating from 1738 to 1816, little changed by the passage of time, will be opened to the public by Historic Charleston Foundation. Pictured here are ten of these homes. THE BRANFORD - HORRY HOUSE 59 Meeting Street c. 1751 THOMAS LEGARE'S HOUSE 90 Church Street c. 1760 Built by Huguenot merchant when Church Street was a lively part of Charleston's business district. Typical piazza, overlooking garden with arched brick wall, makes charming entrance to house filled with family furniture and portraits. HOUSE 39 Church Street c. 1738 One of Charleston's earliest and handsomest examples of Georgian double house, once home of Jacob Motte, treasurer of province, heavily damaged during the bombardment of the Confederate War. CAPERS - HUGER SMITH HOUSE 69 Church Street c. 1745 TOURS HEADQUARTERS AND TOURIST INFORMATION BUREAU 94 Church Street Charleston, S. C. HISTORIC CHARLESTON NOW IS OPENING HER GATES AND DOORS Charlestonians are now welcoming the publie to some of their finest homes. When spring is at its height and the famous gardens are in bloom, owners of eighteen distinguished houses will show them for the benefit of this historic city, to preserve its beauty and its interest for the nation, through TOURS OF HISTORIC HOUSES Fourth Annual Series of Tours Through Private Homes Sponsored by Historic Charleston Foundation MARCH 19 TO APRIL 14, 1951 There will be a series of four tours, with four houses on each tour. Each day, Monday through Friday, there will be a morning and an afternoon tour; each Sunday, with the exception of Easter, an afternoon tour. Houses will be sbown by candlelight on Tuesday and Friday evenings. TOURS ALTERNATE The first two tours, A and B, will be shown Marsh 19 through April 1, and eight homes will be open. The second two tours, C and D, will be shown April 2 through April 14 and eight other houses will be open. The hours are 10 a. m. to 1 p. m. each morning, and 3 p. m. to 6 p. m., each afternoon. On Sundays the hours are 2 p.m. to 6 p.m. Houses are open in the evenings from 8 to 10 p. m. Trained Hostesses On Hand Visitors are conducted through the homes by hostesses. Homes may be visited in any order desired. A tour ticket is good for the entire two week period and entitles the visitor to one admission to each house at any time during the hour the house is open. Transportation when desired will be available at reasonable cost. TARIFF DAYTIME TOURS (A, B, C, D): Fee for each tour $3 plus tax. Fee for combination of A and B, or C and D, $5 plus tax. Special Evening Tours: One house only. Fee: $1, plus tax. For General Information, See Inside Center Spread. For further Information write: Historic Charleston Foundation, 94 Church Street, Charleston, S. C.  TOURS OF CHARLESTON'S HISTORIC HOUSES Schedule for 1951, March 18 through April 15 SPONSORED BY HISTORIC CHARLESTON FOUNDATION Headquarters, 94 Church Street, Charleston, S. C. Telephone 3-1168 Special feature for 1951, Sunday afternoon Tours on Sunday, March 18, April 1, April 8 and April 15. No tour on Easter Sunday. TOUR A Sunday, March 18'2 p.m. to 6 p.m. 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 19, 20, 21, 22 23. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., March 26, 27, 28, 29, 30. WILLIAM HENDRICKS' BUILDINGS, 83 Church Street, c. 1749. A charming bit of imaginative restoration, typical of much that has been done in Charleston recently. Built soon after fire of 1740 by William Hendricks, planter of Christ Church Parish. Restored in 1935 by Mr. and Mrs. Reynolds D. Brown. WILLIAM GIBBES' HOUSE, 64 South Battery, c. 1772. Splendid Georgian mansion, built by William Gibbes at the water side. Has had such owners as the Ret. John Grimke Drayton, who planted the Magnolia Gardens, and the late Hrs. Washington A. Roebling, widow of the builder of the Brooklyn Bridge, who restored house and garden. Home of Mr. and Mrs. John Ashby Farrow. Noted for wonderful furniture, mannificmt ballroom. JOSEPH WINTHROP'S HOUSE, 129 Tradd Street, c. 1797. Restrained Adam style of principal rooms practically in original condition, built by Joseph Winthrop, of New England, who married a sister of Charles Fraser, the miniaturist. Residaice of Admiral and Mrs. William S. Popham. ASHLEY HALL, 172 Rutledge Avenue, c. 1816. Massive Regency house, noted for its spiralling stairway, ornate woodwork and mantels. Once the home of George A. Trenholm, great Charleston merchant and Secretary of the Treasury of the Confederate States. Since 1909 it has bean a famous Southern School for girls. TOUR B Sunday, April 1'2 p.m. to 6 p.m. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., March 19, 20, 21, 22, 23. 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 26, 27, 28, 29, 30. YOUNG-JOHNSON HOUSE, 35 Church Street, c. 1770. Characteristic "single" house, built before Revolution, home of Wilmer Hoffman, well-known sculptor, who restored it and filled it with notable collection of family furniture and objects of art, ably demonstrating the harmonious blending of periods and styles. HARTH-MIDDLETON HOUSE, 68 South Battery, c. 1797. Originally built by John Harth as a typical Adam style single house. In 1843 Henry Augustus middleton, of Weehaw, enlarged it. and the grounds, which now stand on land once occupied by bustling lumber yards and marsh. Noteworthy for garden, now the residence of Mr. and Mrs. Batson L. Hewitt. MRS. WILLIAM HEYWARD'S HOUSE, 31 Legare Street, c. 1789. Built by Hannah Shuhrick Heyward, member of one of greatest rice-planting families of the Low Country. Fine panelling and delicate Adam ornament, particularly noteworthy drawing room with half round bay and palladian window. One of Charleston's haunted houses. Home of Mr. and Mrs. A. T. Smythe. PHILIP PORCHER'S HOUSE, 19 Archdale Street, c. 1765. With its high brick basement -and back and front steps, house reminiscent of old plantation homes. Built by Philip Porcher, who made a fortune planting Indigo. Little changed, it has just come back to the builder's family, and the owners, Mr. and Mrs. Richard G. White, have furnished it with many family pieces. TOUR C Sunday, April 8'2 p.m. to 6 p.m. 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., April 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., April 9, 10, 11, 12, 13. THOMAS LEGARE'S HOUSE, 90 Church Street, c. 1760. Built in handsome mid-Georgian style by well known Huguenot when Church Street was lively part of Charleston's business district. Home of Mr. W. Lucas Simons. Typical piazza, overlooking garden with arched brick walls, makes charming entrance to house filled with family furniture and portraits. COLONEL OTHNIEL BEALE'S HOUSE, 101 East Bay Street, c. 1740. Othniel Beale, immigrant from New England, Colonel of provincial troops in charge of strengthening the town's fortifications, built on this property just after the great fire of 1740. Handsome rooms, panelled with Low Country cypress, show how merchant of Charleston once lived. Home of Mr. and Mrs. Lionel K. Legge. ASHLEY HALL, 172 Rutledge Avenue, c. 1816. Massive Regency house, notable for spiralling stairway, ornate woodwork and mantels. Once home of George A. Trenholm, great Charleston merchant and Secretary of the Treasury of the Confederate States. Since 1909 a famous Southern School for girls. COLONEL WILLIAM RHETT'S HOUSE, 54 Hasell Street, c. 1712. (Note'Open only week of April 2 through 6.) Believed to be oldest house in Charleston, built in reign of flueen Anne by William Rhett, Vice-Admiral of the Province who cleared its coasts of pirates. Birthplace of Wade Hampton, commander of Confederate cavalry, and great governor of South Carolina. Distinguished for unusual Georgian plaster ormaments, exquisite woodwork and furnishings. Home of Mr. and Mrs. Benjamin R. Kittredge, Jr. THOMAS ROSE'S HOUSE, 59 Church Street, c. 1735. (Note'Open only week of April 8 through April 13.) Very handsome early Georgian house. Also said to be haunted, and by a young poet who died from a duel over an actress. Home of Mr. and Mrs. Henry P. Staats. Retains its original panelling, and is furnished with a fine collection of Adam, Chippendale and Hepplewhite. TOUR D Sunday, April 15'2 p.m. to 6 p.m. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., April 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., April 9, 10, 11, 12, 13. CAPERS HUGER-SB1TH HOUSE, 69 Church Street, c. 1745. Fine early example of double house, once the home of Jacob Motte, treasurer of the Province. Bought in 1868, after it had suffered severely in bombardment of Charleston, by Mrs. William Mason Smith. Now home of her granddaughters, Miss Caroline R. Huger Smith, and Miss Alice R. Huger Smith, the distinguished water-colorist. GEORGE EVELEIGH'S HOUSE, 39 Church Street, c. 1738. Built by Eveleigh, whose great Indian trade went as far west as the Mississippi. Its street was a creek when it was built. Long the home of Miss Mary 0. Marshall and her family. Host of the furniture of Charleston origin, and for generations in owner's family. JAMES SHOOLBRED'S HOUSE, 2 Ladson Street, c. 1793. James Shoolbred, first British consul at Charleston, probably built this house when he married Mary, daughter and heiress of Thomas Middleton of Crowfield. Unusual woodwork with fine overmantels. Home of Mr. and Mrs. B. Owen Geer, who have filled its fine rooms with many handsome things. COLOBEL JOHN STUART'S HOUSE, 106 Tradd Street, c. 1772. House represents peak of Georgian design in this part of the world. Built by Colonel Stuart, who had made money in the Indian trade, was Commissioner of Indian Affairs and later lost his home when he took the royalist side during the Revolution. The splendid woodwork, doorways and mantels serve now as admirable home for the fine furniture and splendid portraits of the owners, Mr. and Mrs. John D. Wing. SPECIAL EVENING TOUR Friday Evening, 8 p.m. to 10 p.m., March 23, 30, April 6, 13. BRANFORD-HORRY HOUSE, 59 Meeting Street, c. 1751. This distinquished Georgian double house built by William Branford, about 1830. His grandson, Elias Horry, ex-intendant of Charleston, and president of the South Carolina Railroad, added the porch over the street. The panelled interiors are unusual, and are handsomely furnished with fine English and American pieces of Colonial Charleston. The collection of porcelains is outstanding. The home of Mrs. Percy Gamble Kammerer.
